      "writtenOn": "2019-07-12T06:42:05Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "Is it OK to return (non-nil) err from body even if ctx is canceled while we are waiting for clean to finish? It might be good to return ctx.Err() in that case because we consider (body + clean) as one unit.\nAlso, could you have a corresponding test?",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 37,
        "startChar": 0,
        "endLine": 37,
        "endChar": 20
      },
      "revId": "f34797a25ff0f85a558a98bd7e32124064c31f2a",
      "serverId": "3ce6091f-6c88-37e8-8c75-72f92ae8dfba",
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "fb3f51ad_b9fbe024",
        "filename": "src/chromiumos/tast/host/async.go",
        "patchSetId": 1
      },
      "lineNbr": 37,
      "author": {
        "id": 1118346
      },
      "writtenOn": "2019-07-16T08:41:04Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "I\u0027m hesitant to do that. The strategy here is to return the first encountered error, which is common strategy in Go error handling IMO. What you suggest is to override an previous error, corresponding to code like this in synchronous function:\n\n func f(ctx context.Context) (retErr error) {\n   defer func() {\n     if err :\u003d cleanUp(ctx); err !\u003d nil {\n       retErr \u003d err // retErr is overridden even if it was non-nil\n     }\n   }()\n\n   return doSomething(ctx)\n }\n\nThat said, I\u0027m not sure if it\u0027s a good idea to wait for clean here. It might be an option to just return immediately.",
      "parentUuid": "94742fa8_3ac7964d",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 37,
        "startChar": 0,
        "endLine": 37,
        "endChar": 20
      },
      "revId": "f34797a25ff0f85a558a98bd7e32124064c31f2a",
      "serverId": "3ce6091f-6c88-37e8-8c75-72f92ae8dfba",
      "unresolved": true
    },
